    <h1>Eight Names, One Operation</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Chapter 3 · Rubin 1915, Koffka 1935, Piaget 1975, Laird et al. 1987, Calcagno et al. 2009, Pearl 2009, Lake et al. 2015, Arjovsky et al. 2019</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Six fields independently discovered the same abstract schema: isolate a salient part against a retained background. Each formalized it separately — bi-abduction, figure-ground, equilibration, intervention — with no shared formal definition for the class. Eight names, no crosswalk.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>The citation gap</h2>

    <p>Calcagno et al. (2009) introduced bi-abduction to scale separation-logic analysis at Facebook. Their paper cites Peirce zero times. Rubin (1915) described figure-ground segregation in visual perception. He cited Gestalt colleagues, never the pragmatists. Piaget (1975) formalized equilibration as the mechanism of cognitive development. He cited Piaget. Pearl (2009) built a calculus of interventions for causal inference. He cited Rubin (Donald, not Edgar) — the statistician, not the psychologist. Laird, Rosenbloom, and Newell (1987) formalized chunking in Soar's cognitive architecture. Lake et al. (2015) proposed Bayesian program learning for one-shot concept acquisition. Arjovsky et al. (2019) separated invariant features from spurious correlations in domain generalization.</p>

    <p>Eight entries across six fields. They largely developed in separate citation networks. The pattern recurs: given an observation, separate what demands attention from what can be retained. The words differ — anti-frame, figure, perturbation, treatment variable, surprising fact, invariant feature. The abstract schema is the same.</p>

    <p>Each field defines a concrete mechanism — computational in some cases (bi-abduction, IRM), perceptual or developmental in others (figure-ground, equilibration). Each mechanism takes an input and partitions it: the salient part (signal, figure, novelty) and the retained part (noise, ground, frame). That recurrence is evidence for a shared abstraction, not yet a formal identity. The identity is what Chapter 4 will propose.</p>

    <h2>The table</h2>

    <p>Chapter 2 established that abduction has maximal <a href="/reading/methodeutics/ch02-security-uberty/">uberty</a> — it is the only mode in Peirce's triad that introduces explanatory hypotheses. The question now is whether this fertile, insecure mode is a single abstract schema or a family of unrelated operations that happen to look similar. The table below is the evidence.</p>

