    <p>Read any row. The structure is: take an observation, split it into figure and ground, and name the figure. The figure is the hypothesis — the part that matters, the part that changed, the part that explains. The ground is everything else: the heap that wasn't touched, the schema that didn't break, the background variables held fixed.</p>

    <h2>Reading the entries</h2>

    <h3>Bi-abduction (Calcagno et al. 2009)</h3>

    <p>Separation logic describes heap-manipulating programs with assertions of the form <em>P * F</em>, where <em>P</em> is the precondition for the current operation and <em>F</em> is the frame — the part of the heap the operation doesn't touch. The frame rule says: if the operation is safe given <em>P</em>, it's still safe in the presence of <em>F</em>, because <em>F</em> is disjoint and untouched.</p>

    <p>Bi-abduction infers <em>both</em> pieces simultaneously. Given a command that modifies some heap state, bi-abduction asks: what precondition is missing (the anti-frame), and what heap fragment survives unchanged (the frame)? The anti-frame is the figure. The frame is the ground. This is the operation that powers Facebook's <a href="https://fbinfer.com/">Infer</a> static analyzer — millions of lines of code, analyzed compositionally, because the figure-ground split is modular.</p>

    <h3>Chunking (Laird, Rosenbloom, Newell 1987)</h3>

    <p>In Soar, when the system cannot decide which operator to apply, it hits an impasse and drops into a subgoal. Inside the subgoal, the system reasons until it finds a result. Chunking caches this result as a production rule: the conditions tested during the subgoal become the rule's left-hand side (ground — the superstate conditions that were already true), and the result becomes the right-hand side (figure — the new working-memory elements that resolved the impasse). Next time those conditions arise, the chunk fires directly. No impasse, no subgoal.</p>

    <p>The figure-ground split is automatic. Soar's architecture traces which working-memory elements were tested during the subgoal and which were produced. The tested elements become the ground; the produced elements become the figure. The system doesn't decide what to cache — the architecture decides for it, by recording what was used and what was created.</p>

    <h3>Type inference (Lake, Salakhutdinov, Tenenbaum 2015)</h3>

    <p>Bayesian program learning (BPL) sees a single handwritten character and infers a generative program — a sequence of strokes, a motor plan. The type is the invariant structure: the number of strokes, their relative positions, their topological relations. The token-level variance — pen pressure, speed, slant, jitter — is marginalized out. One example is enough because the model separates what makes the letter that letter (figure) from what makes this particular instance of the letter different from others (ground).</p>

    <p>This is abduction in the Peircean sense: given a surprising observation (a character never seen before), propose a structural explanation (a program that would produce it). The explanation is insecure — it might be wrong, it might attribute structure where there is none — but it is maximally fertile. One example, one hypothesis, and the hypothesis is a program.</p>

    <h3>Figure-ground segregation (Rubin 1915, Koffka 1935)</h3>

    <p>Edgar Rubin's doctoral thesis introduced the figure-ground distinction to perceptual psychology. The <em>Figur</em> is bounded, has shape, and appears in front. The <em>Grund</em> is shapeless, extends behind the figure, and continues underneath it. Rubin's vase demonstrates: you see either a vase (white figure, black ground) or two faces (black figure, white ground), never both simultaneously.</p>

    <p>Koffka generalized this into a principle of perceptual organization: the visual field is not a flat collection of features but a structured partition into regions of different salience. The partition is not in the stimulus — the same pixels produce vase or faces depending on the observer's state. The split is an act of the perceiving system, not a property of the input. This is the phenomenological statement of the operation: figure-ground segregation is something the observer does, not something the world provides.</p>

    <h3>Equilibration (Piaget 1975/1985)</h3>

    <p>Piaget's equilibration is the mechanism by which cognitive structures change. A child has a schema — a stable cognitive structure. A novel element arrives that the schema cannot assimilate without distortion. This is the perturbation (figure). The schema either accommodates — restructures to incorporate the new element — or assimilates — absorbs it without structural change. When accommodation occurs, the schema is permanently altered. When assimilation occurs, the schema is confirmed and the novel element is noise.</p>

    <p>The perturbation is the figure: the element that doesn't fit. The schema is the ground: the structure that was already there. Equilibration is the process of deciding which it is — does the observation challenge the structure, or does the structure absorb the observation? This is precisely the security-uberty tradeoff from <a href="/reading/methodeutics/ch02-security-uberty/">Chapter 2</a>, cast in developmental terms. Assimilation is secure (the schema survives). Accommodation is fertile (the schema changes). Equilibration is the mechanism that navigates between them.</p>

    <h3>Intervention (Pearl 2009)</h3>

    <p>Pearl's <em>do</em>-calculus formalizes the difference between observing and intervening. To observe <em>X=x</em> is to condition on it — the causal structure is unchanged. To intervene <em>do(X=x)</em> is to set it — the incoming causal arrows to <em>X</em> are severed. The treatment variable is the figure: the thing you changed. The background variables <em>U</em> are the ground: held fixed across the intervention.</p>

    <p>The counterfactual contrast <em>Y&#x2081; - Y&#x2080;</em> is the branching version: what would have happened if you had intervened differently? This is abduction's branching degree of freedom. Peirce's economy of research asks which hypothesis to test next. Pearl's counterfactual asks what the outcome would have been under a different intervention. Both select among possible figure-ground splits.</p>

    <h3>Abduction (Peirce 1903)</h3>

    <p>Peirce's own formulation is the most general. A surprising fact <em>C</em> is observed. If <em>A</em> were true, <em>C</em> would be a matter of course. Therefore there is reason to suspect <em>A</em>. The surprising fact is the figure — what stands out against settled expectations. The settled expectations are the ground — the background model against which the surprise registers.</p>

    <p>Peirce's formulation is also the most honest about the insecurity. "There is reason to suspect <em>A</em>" is not "A is true" or even "A is probable." It is a claim about where to look next. Abduction doesn't produce knowledge. It produces questions. That is why its <a href="/reading/methodeutics/ch02-security-uberty/">uberty is maximal and its security is minimal</a> — you get a new direction, not a new certainty.</p>

    <h3>Invariant risk minimization (Arjovsky et al. 2019)</h3>

    <p>IRM separates features into two classes: invariant features that predict the label across all training environments, and spurious features that predict the label in some environments but not others. A cow on grass is reliably bovine in a farm dataset. On a beach, the grass feature fails. The cow feature is invariant (figure). The grass feature is spurious (ground).</p>

    <p>The branching version is counterfactual policy evaluation: would this feature still predict the outcome in a different environment? IRM operationalizes the split by training a classifier that performs well across multiple environments simultaneously. Features that survive the distributional shift are figure; features that don't are ground. The operation is the same: partition, separate, name the invariant.</p>

    <h2>The common structure</h2>

    <p>Strip the vocabulary. Every row in the table implements the same three-step operation:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Observe</strong> — take in a state (heap, visual field, schema, dataset, surprising fact).</li>
      <li><strong>Partition</strong> — split the state into two parts: what matters (figure, anti-frame, perturbation, treatment variable, surprising fact, invariant feature) and what doesn't (ground, frame, schema, background, settled expectations, spurious feature).</li>
      <li><strong>Name the figure</strong> — the figure becomes the hypothesis, the explanation, the type, the result. It is the new idea. The ground is everything the new idea doesn't touch.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>The branching column is the fourth step that some formulations include: what if the partition were different? Tri-abduction branches on the heap state. Multistability branches on the percept. Reflective abstraction branches on the schema. Counterfactual contrast branches on the intervention. Economy of research branches on the hypothesis. They are all asking the same question: given that this partition is one of many possible partitions, which partition is the right one?</p>

    <p>This is why the operation is insecure. There is no deductive guarantee that the partition is correct. The same observation admits multiple figure-ground splits. Rubin's vase is the literal demonstration: the same stimulus, two partitions, both valid, mutually exclusive. Security would require a unique correct partition. Uberty requires exactly the opposite — multiple candidate partitions, each proposing a different explanation, each fertile in a different direction.</p>

    <h2>Why they don't cite each other</h2>

    <p>The citation gap is not an accident. It has three causes, and understanding them explains why the operation stayed unnamed for a century.</p>

    <p><strong>Vocabulary isolation.</strong> Separation logic speaks heap fragments and entailment. Gestalt psychology speaks percepts and phenomenal fields. Causal inference speaks structural equations and counterfactuals. The vocabularies are so different that the shared structure is invisible. A PL researcher reading Koffka would see psychology. A psychologist reading Calcagno would see notation. Neither would see the same operation.</p>

    <p><strong>Institutional boundaries.</strong> Computer science publishes at POPL and PLDI. Psychology publishes in <em>Psychological Review</em>. Causal inference publishes in <em>JRSS-B</em> and <em>Biometrika</em>. These communities do not attend the same conferences, do not read the same journals, and do not share reviewers. Cross-pollination requires someone fluent in at least two of these languages. Peirce was such a person, but he died in 1914, before any of the modern formalizations existed.</p>

    <p><strong>The anti-formalism norm.</strong> Philosophy has discussed abduction extensively, but largely in the "inference to the best explanation" (IBE) tradition following Harman (1965). IBE debates center on justification — is IBE a legitimate inference rule? — not on formalization. The question "what is the operation, precisely?" is considered reductive by philosophers and unmotivated by engineers. The result: philosophers who know the history don't formalize, and engineers who formalize don't know the history.</p>

    <h2>Why it matters</h2>

    <p>Independent discovery is strong evidence that something real is being discovered. When one person names a pattern, it could be pareidolia. When eight groups across six fields name the same pattern — using different words, from different starting points, with different motivations — the pattern is probably in the territory, not the map.</p>

    <p>But "probably real" is not "formally defined." The table shows the phenomenon exists. It does not show what the phenomenon <em>is</em>. We have eight instances and no definition. We have a name for each instance and no name for the class. We can point at examples of figure-ground separation, but we cannot write down the operation in a way that a machine could execute — the way modus ponens is written down for deduction, or Bayes' rule is written down for induction.</p>

    <p>This is the gap that Part I of this textbook has been building toward. Chapter 1 named the three modes and established that one is missing from the formal canon. Chapter 2 ranked them by security and uberty and showed that the missing mode is the maximally fertile one. This chapter has shown that the missing mode is not missing from practice — it appears everywhere, under eight names, with the same structure. What is missing is the formalization.</p>

    <p>A table is not a formalization. It is evidence that a formalization should exist. The next chapter proposes the primitive: <strong>diff</strong>.</p>

